{"title_page": "Plebgate", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n[[File:Official portrait of Mr Andrew Mitchell.jpg|thumb|[[Andrew Mitchell]], [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sutton Coldfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton Coldfield]], who was involved in the scandal.|right|284x284px]]\n\n'''\"Plebgate\"''' (or '''\"Plodgate\"''', '''\"Gategate\"''') was a British political scandal which started in September 2012. The trigger was an altercation between [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative MP]] [[Andrew Mitchell]], who resigned from his position as the Government [[Chief Whip]] because of the incident, and the police. Plebgate gained notoriety initially for the conduct claimed of Mitchell and again two months later when, subsequent to Mitchell's resignation, [[CCTV]] and other evidence was revealed which appeared to call into question some of the evidence against him. \n\nLeaked police logs, later apparently backed up by eyewitness evidence, suggested that Mitchell had sworn at police officers on duty at [[Downing Street]] and called them \"[[Pleb#Modern usage|plebs]]\" (a [[pejorative]] word signifying someone of low social class) when they refused to open the main gate for him as he attempted to leave with his bicycle, telling him to walk through the adjacent pedestrian gate instead. Mitchell apologised but denied using the words claimed and in particular calling police officers \"plebs\". However, finding his position untenable amid the media storm surrounding the incident, he resigned from office a month later.\n\nThe story returned to the headlines a few months later, when CCTV footage was released to the media which threw into doubt the police version of events and when it was revealed that an email purporting to be from a member of the public, which had backed up the accounts given in the official police log, was actually sent by a serving police officer who had not been present at the scene. The [[Metropolitan Police]] investigated the incident as Operation Alice.\n\nThe affair was revisited again in October 2013, after a report from the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]] (IPCC) concluded three officers had given a false account of a meeting they had with Mitchell at his constituency office in October 2012, and that the findings of a subsequent investigation had been changed just in time to recommend no disciplinary action be taken against them. After both [[Home Secretary]] [[Theresa May]] and [[Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]] criticised the conduct of the officers involved, the officers issued a statement in which they apologised for misleading the public. At the [[Old Bailey]], PC Keith Wallis subsequently admitted falsely claiming to have witnessed the incident and was sentenced to 12 months in prison.\n\nOnce the criminal trials were out of the way, Mitchell sued for libel. The judge ruled \"on the balance of probabilities\" that Mitchell had said \"the words alleged or something so close to them as to amount to the same including the politically toxic word pleb.\"\n\n==Incident and initial aftermath==\n[[File:Plebgate.jpg|thumb|right|Armed police at the gates to [[Downing Street]]]]\n[[File:Downing.street.gates.london.arp.jpg|thumb|Pedestrian gate to the left, car gates at centre]]\nOn the evening of Wednesday 19 September 2012, at approximately 7:30 pm, Mitchell left the office of the Chief Whip at 9 Downing Street, the street containing the [[official residence]] of the Prime Minister ([[10 Downing Street|Number Ten]]) and [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] ([[11 Downing Street|Number 11]]) and therefore under heavy security. Mitchell, who was cycling, swore when a police officer told him to exit Downing Street through the pedestrian gate rather than by the main gate.<ref name=telown>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9764186/Plebgate-Andrew-Mitchell-gives-own-account-of-Downing-Street-exchange.html |title=Plebgate: Andrew Mitchell gives own account of Downing Street exchange |work=The Telegraph |date=23 December 2012}}</ref> The official police log<ref name=fulllog>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9564006/In-full-Police-log-detailing-Andrew-Mitchells-pleb-rant.html |title=In full: Police log detailing Andrew Mitchell's 'pleb' rant |work=The Telegraph |date=24 September 2012}}</ref> of the incident states that Mitchell said:\n\n{{quote|''\"Best you learn your fucking place. You don't run this fucking government ... You're fucking plebs.\"''<ref name=tellog>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9563847/Police-log-reveals-details-of-Andrew-Mitchells-pleb-rant.html |title=Police log reveals details of Andrew Mitchell's 'pleb' rant |work=The Telegraph |date=24 September 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nThe log reported Mitchell as saying:\n\n{{quote|''\"you haven\u2019t heard the last of this.\"<ref name=tellog />''}}\n\nOn Thursday 20 September, before the incident was publicly reported, an email<ref name=\"email\">{{cite news |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-email-letter-plebgate-pleb-police |title=Revealed: Mitchell 'plebgate' row eyewitness email |work=Channel 4 News |date=20 December 2012}}</ref> was also received by [[John Randall (UK politician)|John Randall, MP]], the Government's Deputy Chief Whip. It appeared to offer independent corroboration of the version of events in the police log. The author stated he was a member of the public who had been present outside the gates of Downing Street at the time, with his nephew from Hong Kong;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/dec/19/andrew-mitchell-row-timeline |title=Andrew Mitchell row \u2013 timeline |date=19 December 2012 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and that the incident had been witnessed by other tourists nearby.<ref name=cctv>{{cite news |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |work=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012}}</ref> This email later proved to be quite false and in fact came from a police officer who had not been present.<ref name=c4/>\n\nThese allegations became known in the media as '''\"Plebgate\"'''.<ref name=telown /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-announces-resignation-over-plebgate-claims |title=Andrew Mitchell announces resignation over 'plebgate' claims|work=Channel 4 News |date=19 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chief-whip-andrew-mitchell-resigns-over-plebgate-8218881.html|title=Chief Whip Andrew Mitchell resigns over 'Plebgate'|work=The Independent|date=19 October 2012}}</ref> Members of the [[West Midlands Police|West Midlands]] branch of the [[Police Federation of England and Wales]], [[Shadow Home Secretary]] [[Yvette Cooper]] and a [[Editorial|leader column]] in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' called on Mitchell to resign or be sacked.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/9602119/Andrew-Mitchell-must-step-down.html |title=Telegraph View \u2013 Andrew Mitchell must step down |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nThe affair has occasionally been referred to as '''\"Plodgate\"''' (\"[[wikt:plod#Etymology 3|plod]]\" being mildly derogatory [[British slang]] for a police officer).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2012/12/will-the-plod-gate-revelations-change-how-voters-think-about-class-attacks/|title=Will 'plod-gate' make voters more sceptical of class-based political attacks?|work=The Spectator |date=23 December 2012|accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Week]]'' magazine called it \"'''Gategate'''\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/politics/gategate/49169/gategate-friends-ids-take-pleasure-andrew-mitchell-gaffe  |title=Gategate: Andrew Mitchell fails to deny calling police \u2018plebs\u2019  |work=The Week |date=24 September 2012}}</ref> which was picked up by ''[[Business Insider]]'', saying that this use of the [[-gate|-gate suffix for scandals]] had taken \"the practice to its logical conclusion\" as a \"new height of absurdity\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Adam |title=The Latest Political Scandal In London Has The Best Name Yet |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/gategate-the-latest-absurd-uk-scandal-2012-9?r=US&IR=T |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\n==Apologies and eventual resignation==\nMitchell apologised on 21 September, saying \"I admit I did not treat the police with the respect they deserve\", but he denied swearing or calling the officers \"plebs\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19671093 |title=Chief Whip Andrew Mitchell apologises to police |publisher=BBC News |date=21 September 2012}}</ref> However, he later admitted saying: \"I thought you guys were supposed to fucking help us.\"<ref name=telown /> John Tully, chairman of the [[Metropolitan Police Federation]], said that Mitchell's account was contradicted by notes made by two officers at the scene.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.sky.com/story/988170/mitchell-faces-calls-to-quit-over-police-row |title=Mitchell Row: PC's Widower Urges PM To Act |date=22 September 2012\n|publisher=Sky News}}</ref> The Chairman of the [[Police Federation of England and Wales]] commented that \"It is hard to fathom how someone who holds the police in such contempt could be allowed to hold a public office. Mr Mitchell's half-hearted apology for the comments made whilst leaving Downing Street will do little to build bridges with the police\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polfed.org/newsroom/554.aspx |title=Federation response to comments made by Chief Whip, Andrew Mitchell |publisher=Police Federation of England and Wales |date=21 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nFive days after the event, on 24 September, Mitchell apologised a second time for his behaviour, saying \"I didn't show the police the amount of respect which I should have done\", but stated that he did not use the words that had been attributed to him. He did not specify which words he was referring to. John Tully said \"It is not the words, police officers are quite thick skinned, what infuriates me here is that a minister [Andrew Mitchell] is saying police officers are liars. There is a clear difference of opinion, and we need to establish what happened.\"<ref name=telref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9562468/Andrew-Mitchell-Police-refuse-second-apology-as-calls-for-inquiry-grow.html |title=Andrew Mitchell: Police refuse second apology as calls for inquiry grow |work=The Telegraph |date=24 September 2012}}</ref> The same day, [[Secretary of the Cabinet (United Kingdom)|Cabinet Secretary]] [[Jeremy Heywood|Sir Jeremy Heywood]] confirmed in a letter to Shadow Home Secretary Yvette Cooper that there would be no inquiry into Andrew Mitchell's outburst because, although the outburst was disappointing, the officer had accepted Mitchell's apology.<ref name=BBC19707950>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19707950 |title=Andrew Mitchell avoids investigation over police row |publisher=BBC News |date=24 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nMitchell's apologies failed to end the criticism, and media commentators and political opponents continued to call for his resignation.<ref name=BBC19922026>{{cite news |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19922026 |title=Andrew Mitchell resigns over police comments row |date=19 October 2012}}</ref> Finally, Mitchell resigned on 19 October, stating, \"It has become clear to me that whatever the rights and wrongs of the matter I will not be able to fulfill my duties as we both would wish. [...] Nor is it fair to continue to put my family and colleagues through this upsetting and damaging publicity\". He continued to maintain that he had not used the word \"pleb\". The Police Federation of England and Wales issued a statement that it regarded his resignation as the end of the matter, and would seek no further action.<ref name=BBC19922026 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19922026|title=Andrew Mitchell resigns over police comments row |publisher=BBC News |date=20 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Doubts over police version of events==\nIn mid-December 2012, CCTV footage of the incident was released, which Mitchell insisted backed up his version of events. The footage shows a brief interaction between Mitchell and the police and there was no crowd of tourists outside the gates.<ref name=cctv />\n\nOn 18 December 2012, journalist [[Michael Crick]] and former [[The Cook Report]] producer Philip Braund identified the author of the 20 September email as a police officer and challenged his account. The officer admitted that he was not present and that the email was false.<ref name=c4>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |publisher=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012 |timecaption=\"Plebgate row\", event occurs at |time=16:00}}</ref> Police logs and the supporting email had both claimed that \"several members of the public\" were present, that they had heard the exchange and were \"visibly shocked\". The email alleged that \"Other people/tourists standing with us were also shocked and some were even, inadvertently, filming the incident\". However, the CCTV footage shows only a single member of the public stopping to look on from an otherwise empty section of street immediately outside the gates.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |publisher=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012 |timecaption=\"Plebgate row\", event occurs at |time=07:20}}</ref>\n\nIt further transpired that Police Federation officers from around the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] who met with Mitchell had claimed he refused to give his side of events, a claim thrown into question by a recording of that meeting.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |publisher=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012 |timecaption=\"Plebgate row\", event occurs at |time=09:16}}</ref> Mitchell{{mdash}}the MP for [[Sutton Coldfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton Coldfield]] in the West Midlands{{mdash}}had met with three representatives from the [[West Midlands Police|West Midlands]], [[Warwickshire Police|Warwickshire]] and [[West Mercia Police|West Mercia]] forces at his constituency office on 12 October to discuss the incident, after which the officers gave interviews about what had been discussed at the meeting. They claimed Mitchell had not given a full account of the disagreement, but a transcript of the recording he made indicated he had spoken at length about the incident.<ref name=Guardian-2013-10-16/>\n\n==Operation Alice==\nFollowing these revelations, calls were made for the events to be fully investigated. The Metropolitan Police revealed that the investigation, which had started shortly after the leak of the police log,<ref name=BBC19707950 /> now had a team of thirty officers investigating the allegations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pleb row: Calls for inquiry into Andrew Mitchell case |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/plebgate-met-promises-fast-response-to-andrew-mitchell-row |work=Channel 4 News |date=19 December 2012}}</ref> The operation, \"Operation Alice\", was led by the head of the Metropolitan Police's [[Directorate of Professional Standards]], Deputy Assistant Commissioner [[Pat Gallan]].<ref name=bbc20795489>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20795489 |title='Plebgate': Second man arrested in Metropolitan Police inquiry |publisher=BBC News |date=20 December 2012}}</ref> On 23 December, the [[Metropolitan Police Commissioner]] [[Bernard Hogan-Howe]] returned from his holiday to promise \"a ruthless search for the truth\" of the affair.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-20829901|title='Plebgate': Met Police vows 'ruthless' search for truth|publisher=BBC News|date=23 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported on 24 March 2013 that ten police officers and one civilian were suspected of involvement.<ref name=tel10>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9951254/Ten-police-officers-investigated-over-Plebgate-row-that-cost-Andrew-Mitchell-his-job.html |title=Ten police officers investigated over 'Plebgate' row that cost Andrew Mitchell his job |date=24 March 2013 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Seven of those officers and the one civilian fell under Operation Alice, with the investigation into the three Police Federation officers, Ken Mackaill, Chris Jones & Stuart Hinton,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.policeoracle.com/news/Police+Performance/2013/Mar/26/More-Fed-Officials-Face-Plebgate-Probe_62605.html |title=More Fed Officials Face 'Plebgate' Probe |work=Police Oracle |date=26 March 2013}}</ref> being a separate investigation by the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]].<ref name=tel10 />\n\nThe police submitted their report to the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] on 28 March. It contained evidence of alleged leaks, but not that officers had lied about what Mitchell said. The CPS indicated that it was unhappy with the file, referring to it as \"initial papers\" and saying that they were awaiting the conclusion of the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/mar/28/lebgate-file-contains-no-evidence-that-police-lied |title='Plebgate' file passed to prosecutors contains no evidence that police lied |date=29 March 2013 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> At the same time, Mitchell started libel proceedings against ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', the paper that broke the story.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21969990 |title=Andrew Mitchell to sue Sun newspaper over 'plebgate' |date=29 March 2013 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 31 March, as a result of the apparent leaking of the report, he lodged a complaint with the IPCC, accusing the police of a continued campaign to destroy his career.  [[Keith Vaz]], chairman of the [[Home Affairs Select Committee|Commons Home Affairs committee]], said that this illustrated why his committee had always called for the investigation to be run by the IPCC rather than by the police themselves.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/andrew-mitchell-complains-to-police-watchdog-over-scotland-yard-handling-of-plebgate-row-report-8555427.html |title=Andrew Mitchell complains to police watchdog over Scotland Yard handling of 'Plebgate' row report  |date=31 March 2013 |work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2013, Operation Alice had cost an estimated \u00a3144,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-22117380 |title='Plebgate': Police inquiry costs reach \u00a3144,000 |date=11 April 2013 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2014, it was reported that the investigation's conclusion revealed the police had obtained the mobile phone records of the Political Editor of ''The Sun'' without his knowledge, through use of the [[Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000]], and in breach of the usual safeguards for the protection of journalistic sources. They were thereby able to unmask the identity of the whistle-blower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/leveson-inquiry/11077481/A-perfect-example-of-the-need-for-a-free-press.html|title=A perfect example of the need for a free press|first=Telegraph|last=View|date=5 September 2014|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Investigations and arrests===\nIn March 2013, three officers from the [[Parliamentary and Diplomatic Protection]] were arrested: one on suspicion of [[misconduct in a public office]], one on suspicion of unauthorised disclosure of information to the media and one on suspicion of both offences.<ref name=bbcheld>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21299860 |title='Plebgate': Police officer held over inquiry |publisher=BBC News |date=1 February 2013}}</ref> Another man, a relative of one of the arrested officers,<ref name=guarpf>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/mar/24/plebgate-police-federation-andrew-mitchell |title=Plebgate affair: Police Federation staff quizzed over Andrew Mitchell remarks |date=24 March 2013 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> was arrested on suspicion of \"intentionally encouraging or assisting the commission of an indictable offence\", relating to misconduct in a public office.<ref name=bbcheld /> In addition, another four members of the Diplomatic Protection Group became the subject of disciplinary investigations.<ref name=guarpf /> Under a separate but related inquiry by the IPCC, three members of the Police Federation were investigated for alleged misconduct over comments they made to the media.<ref name=tel10 />\n\nIn June 2013 two more arrests were made, with one of those arrested being a serving police officer. The officer, one of the four Diplomatic Protection officers already undergoing disciplinary investigation, was arrested on suspicion of misconduct in a public office and the civilian on suspicion of assisting an offender.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22919576 |title=Two arrested in 'plebgate' probe |publisher=BBC News |date=15 June 2013}}</ref> In September 2013 it was revealed eight people had been bailed over the issue, including five police officers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24230733 |title=Police Officers Bailed |publisher=BBC |date=24 September 2013}}</ref> The lengthy investigation was criticised by the former [[Director of Public Prosecutions]], [[Ken Macdonald]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24140199 |title='Plebgate' inquiry delay criticised by ex-DPP |publisher=BBC |date=18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Criminal conviction of PC Keith Wallis ===\nOn 10 January 2014, Police Constable Keith Wallis pleaded guilty at the Central Criminal Court, the [[Old Bailey]], to a charge of [[misconduct in a public office]] relating to the email he had sent to [[John Randall MP]]. This prompted the Metropolitan Police Commissioner, Sir [[Bernard Hogan-Howe]], to issue a public apology to Andrew Mitchell:\n\n::\"The evidence against PC Wallis was such that he pleaded guilty. To lie about witnessing something and provide a false account falls way below the standards that I and his colleagues expect of officers. His actions have also negatively impacted upon public trust and confidence in the integrity of police officers. I would also like to apologise to Mr Mitchell that a Met officer clearly lied about seeing him behaving in a certain manner. I will be writing to him offering to meet and apologise in person. I expect my officers to serve the public without fear or favour. Where officers break the law they must expect to be held to account and answer for what they have done.\"<ref>{{cite news| last1=Davenport| first1=Justin| last2=Cecil| first2=Nicholas| date= 10 January 2014| title=Plebgate scandal: Met police apology to Andrew Mitchell after officer admits lie| url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/plebgate-scandal-met-police-apology-to-andrew-mitchell-after-officer-admits-lie-9051453.html| newspaper=London Evening Standard|location=London| publisher=Evening Standard Limited}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2014, Wallis was sentenced to twelve months imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-26064536 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate' PC Keith Wallis jailed for a year |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Seven findings of police misconduct===\nSeven police officers were found to have committed misconduct in relation to Plebgate, one criminally, three at the level of [[gross misconduct]] and three more as misconduct but not gross misconduct requiring dismissal from the service. Specifically:\n\n* on 26 February 2014 Keith Wallis was dismissed for his criminal conduct in this matter and undisclosed business interests;\n* on 26 February 2014 James Glanville was also dismissed for gross misconduct in data handling <ref name=BBC-26Feb2014>{{cite news|title=Met pair dismissed over 'Plebgate'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26358662|accessdate=26 February 2014|publisher=BBC News|date=26 February 2014}}</ref>\n* on 30 April 2014 PC Gillian Weatherley was also dismissed for gross misconduct for leaks to the press.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24548645 |title='Plebgate' row: Timeline |publisher=BBC |date=30 April 2014|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref>\n* on 21 May 2014 Susan Johnson was dismissed for gross misconduct \"in relation to honesty and integrity; confidentiality; discreditable conduct and challenging and reporting improper conduct\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/plebgate-officers-keith-wallis-james-glanville-dismissed-metropolitan-police-1438052 |title='Plebgate' row: Timeline |publisher=BBC |date=21 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n* on 23 May an allegation against PC James Addison was found \"not proven\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27540822 |title='Plebgate' affair: No misconduct by officer |publisher=BBC |date=23 May 2014}}</ref>\n* Three further officers were found guilty of lower level misconduct.\n\n===Federation officers===\nThe IPCC investigation of the three Federation officers, Chris Jones, Stuart Hinton and Ken MacKaill, was on hold for much of 2014, pending a judicial review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-25705250 |title='Plebgate' affair: Police Federation launches legal action |publisher=BBC |date=12 January 2014}}</ref> However, on 3 November 2014, this application was unsuccessful, with the three forces' investigations branded by the administrative court \"a car crash\" and so legally flawed that they were \"invalid and of no effect\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/plebgate-probe-decision-legally-flawed-7893374|title=Plebgate probe decision 'legally flawed'|first=James|last=Cartledge|date=7 October 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nTwo of these officers were also accused of lying to Parliament in their evidence to the Home Affairs Select Committee in the account they gave of their disciplinary record (stating they had no record when in fact they did), and were recalled by the committee to justify this.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Townsend |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/nov/03/plebgate-police-federation-select-committee |title=Plebgate police told: apologise or face a charge of contempt &#124; The Observer |work=The Guardian }}</ref> They subsequently apologised.\n\n==IPCC conclusions==\n\nWest Mercia Police launched an investigation into the conduct of the three police officers who spoke with Mitchell at his constituency office, but concluded they should not be disciplined.<ref name=Birmingham-Mail-2013-10-18>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/midland-chief-constables-quizzed-plebgate-6203811 |title=Midland chief constables to be quizzed about 'Plebgate' row at select committee |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> On 15 October 2013, the IPCC criticised three Police Federation Officers for their version of events. The Home Secretary, [[Theresa May]], was also critical, saying the police were wrong to say they had no case to answer and calling for the officers to be disciplined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10381529/Discipline-Plebgate-police-and-say-sorry-to-Andrew-Mitchell-Theresa-May-tells-forces.html |title=Discipline Plebgate police and say sorry to Andrew Mitchell, Theresa May tells forces |author=Martin Evans |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 October 2013 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24536328 |title='Plebgate' police officers' honesty queried |publisher=BBC |date=15 October 2013 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> At [[Prime Minister's Questions]] on 16 October 2013, David Cameron said that Mitchell was \"owed an apology\" over the Plebgate affair.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24546370 |publisher=BBC News |title=Plebgate: PM says police owe Andrew Mitchell apology  |date=16 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe findings of the IPCC report were criticised by the three police forces concerned, as well as by the [[Police and Crime Commissioner]] for Warwickshire, [[Ron Ball]]. This prompted the IPCC's Deputy Chair, [[Deborah Glass]], to respond with clarification of its conclusions. In a letter to Ball, Glass said that West Mercia had changed its mind over whether to discipline the officers before the final publication of its report.<ref name=Guardian-2013-10-16>{{cite news|first=Nicholas |last=Watt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/16/plebgate-watchdog-police-watered-conclusions-investigation |title=Plebgate: watchdog says police watered down conclusions of investigation |newspaper=The Guardian |date=16 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> Her comments led to media speculation that senior police officers could have interfered with the investigation.<ref name=BBC-2013-10-18>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-24583765 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate' row prompts West Mercia review  |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> Ball subsequently requested a review of West Mercia's inquiry. \"That is a very serious allegation and I want to understand the exact circumstances of the investigative approval process.\"<ref name=BBC-2013-10-18/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/437608/Police-best-in-the-world-insists-PM |title=Police best in the world insists PM |newspaper=Daily Express |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> West Mercia then launched an investigation into issues raised by the IPCC.<ref name=BBC-2013-10-18/>\n\nOn 21 October 2013, the three officers concerned{{mdash}}Ken MacKaill, Stuart Hinton, and Chris Jones{{mdash}}issued a statement in which they apologised for their \"poor judgement\" in briefing the media about their meeting, and said that they did not intend to mislead the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24615491 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate' meeting police apologise for briefing  |date=21 October 2013 |accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref> Along with their respective Chief Constables, the three officers appeared before the [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] on 23 October in which they told MPs their account of the meeting with Mitchell had been \"accurate\" and they stood by it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24629610 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate': Police officers stand by account of Mitchell meeting  |date=23 October 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref> The Committee subsequently called them back, believing that they had misled it. In November 2013 the IPCC announced it would conduct its own investigation into the behaviour of the officers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24787557 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate': Officers face fresh inquiry over Mitchell meeting  |date=3 November 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref> In the wake of the announcement, Ron Ball expressed his concerns about the legality of a new investigation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/news/10781512.New_Plebgate_probe__may_not_be_legally_sound____police_commissioner/ |title=New Plebgate probe 'may not be legally sound' \u2013 police commissioner |newspaper=Worcester News |publisher=Newsquest |date=3 November 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHome Secretary Theresa May referred to this event, along with others, in a speech on 21 May 2014 which demanded the police address issues of honesty and integrity and that the Federation reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27504422 |title=Theresa May urges Police Federation reform |publisher=BBC |date=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Libel trial==\nOn 17 November 2014 a [[Civil law (legal system)|civil]] [[English defamation law|libel case]] for the allegations began oral hearings at the [[Royal Courts of Justice]], before [[John Mitting|Mr Justice Mitting]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/plebgate-trial-sifts-fiction-from-fact-pc-plod-is-the-toyland-constable-is-he-not-9866524.html|title=Plebgate trial sifts fiction from fact|publisher=}}</ref> In these proceedings two cases were joined: the alleged libel of Mitchell by ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', and, alternatively, the alleged libel of PC Rowland by Mitchell.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Darwar|first1=Anil|title=Plebgate MP in \u201816 other clashes\u2019|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/526710/Plebgate-MP-16-other-clashes|accessdate=17 November 2014|publisher=Express Newspapers|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> One of the alleged incidents, which had occurred in November 2005, involved Mitchell claiming that he was too important to stop for a police officer, and a direct insult addressed to the officer involved.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mitchell v News Group Newspapers Ltd [2014] EWHC 3590 (QB) (31 October 2014)|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/QB/2014/3590.html|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mitchell decision considers court\u2019s approach to admitting evidence of \"similar facts\"|url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=5c8ef65e-fdb6-4703-899a-bfc565ada751|accessdate=17 November 2014|date=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November Mr Justice Mitting found: \"I am satisfied at least on the balance of probabilities that Mr Mitchell did speak the words alleged or something so close to them as to amount to the same including the politically toxic word pleb.\" In consequence Mitchell lost the libel cases and became liable for both the ''Sun''{{'}}s and PC Rowland's costs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-30235009|title=Andrew Mitchell 'probably called police plebs', judge rules |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=27 November 2014 |website=BBC News | accessdate=27 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Downing Street}}\n\n[[Category:History of the Metropolitan Police]]\n[[Category:Police misconduct in England]]\n[[Category:Police operations in the United Kingdom|A]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2012 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2012 in London]]\n[[Category:2012 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Downing Street]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n[[File:Official portrait of Mr Andrew Mitchell.jpg|thumb|[[Andrew Mitchell]], [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Sutton Coldfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton Coldfield]], who was involved in the scandal.|right|284x284px]]\n\n'''\"Plebgate\"''' (or '''\"Plodgate\"''', '''\"Gategate\"''') was a British political scandal which started in September 2012. The trigger was an altercation between [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative MP]] [[Andrew Mitchell]], who resigned from his position as the Government [[Chief Whip]] because of the incident, and the police. Plebgate gained notoriety initially for the conduct claimed of Mitchell and again two months later when, subsequent to Mitchell's resignation, [[CCTV]] and other evidence was revealed which appeared to call into question some of the evidence against him. \n\nLeaked police logs, later apparently backed up by eyewitness evidence, suggested that Mitchell had sworn at police officers on duty at [[Downing Street]] and called them \"[[Pleb#Modern usage|plebs]]\" (a [[pejorative]] word signifying someone of low social class) when they refused to open the main gate for him as he attempted to leave with his bicycle, telling him to walk through the adjacent pedestrian gate instead. Mitchell apologised but denied using the words claimed and in particular calling police officers \"plebs\". However, finding his position untenable amid the media storm surrounding the incident, he resigned from office a month later.\n\nThe story returned to the headlines a few months later, when CCTV footage was released to the media which threw into doubt the police version of events and when it was revealed that an email purporting to be from a member of the public, which had backed up the accounts given in the official police log, was actually sent by a serving police officer who had not been present at the scene. The [[Metropolitan Police]] investigated the incident as Operation Alice.\n\nThe affair was revisited again in October 2013, after a report from the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]] (IPCC) concluded three officers had given a false account of a meeting they had with Mitchell at his constituency office in October 2012, and that the findings of a subsequent investigation had been changed just in time to recommend no disciplinary action be taken against them. After both [[Home Secretary]] [[Theresa May]] and [[Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]] criticised the conduct of the officers involved, the officers issued a statement in which they apologised for misleading the public. At the [[Old Bailey]], PC Keith Wallis subsequently admitted falsely claiming to have witnessed the incident and was sentenced to 12 months in prison.\n\nOnce the criminal trials were out of the way, Mitchell sued for libel. The judge ruled \"on the balance of probabilities\" that Mitchell had said \"the words alleged or something so close to them as to amount to the same including the politically toxic word pleb.\"\n\n==Incident and initial aftermath==\n[[File:Plebgate.jpg|thumb|right|Armed police at the gates to [[Downing Street]]]]\n[[File:Downing.street.gates.london.arp.jpg|thumb|Pedestrian gate to the left, car gates at centre]]\nOn the evening of Wednesday 19 September 2012, at approximately 7:30 pm, Mitchell left the office of the Chief Whip at 9 Downing Street, the street containing the [[official residence]] of the Prime Minister ([[10 Downing Street|Number Ten]]) and [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] ([[11 Downing Street|Number 11]]) and therefore under heavy security. Mitchell, who was cycling, swore when a police officer told him to exit Downing Street through the pedestrian gate rather than by the main gate.<ref name=telown>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9764186/Plebgate-Andrew-Mitchell-gives-own-account-of-Downing-Street-exchange.html |title=Plebgate: Andrew Mitchell gives own account of Downing Street exchange |work=The Telegraph |date=23 December 2012}}</ref> The official police log<ref name=fulllog>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9564006/In-full-Police-log-detailing-Andrew-Mitchells-pleb-rant.html |title=In full: Police log detailing Andrew Mitchell's 'pleb' rant |work=The Telegraph |date=24 September 2012}}</ref> of the incident states that Mitchell said:\n\n{{quote|''\"Best you learn your fucking place. You don't run this fucking government ... You're fucking plebs.\"''<ref name=tellog>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9563847/Police-log-reveals-details-of-Andrew-Mitchells-pleb-rant.html |title=Police log reveals details of Andrew Mitchell's 'pleb' rant |work=The Telegraph |date=24 September 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nThe log reported Mitchell as saying:\n\n{{quote|''\"you haven\u2019t heard the last of this.\"<ref name=tellog />''}}\n\nOn Thursday 20 September, before the incident was publicly reported, an email<ref name=\"email\">{{cite news |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-email-letter-plebgate-pleb-police |title=Revealed: Mitchell 'plebgate' row eyewitness email |work=Channel 4 News |date=20 December 2012}}</ref> was also received by [[John Randall (UK politician)|John Randall, MP]], the Government's Deputy Chief Whip. It appeared to offer independent corroboration of the version of events in the police log. The author stated he was a member of the public who had been present outside the gates of Downing Street at the time, with his nephew from Hong Kong;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/dec/19/andrew-mitchell-row-timeline |title=Andrew Mitchell row \u2013 timeline |date=19 December 2012 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and that the incident had been witnessed by other tourists nearby.<ref name=cctv>{{cite news |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |work=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012}}</ref> This email later proved to be quite false and in fact came from a police officer who had not been present.<ref name=c4/>\n\nThese allegations became known in the media as '''\"Plebgate\"'''.<ref name=telown /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-announces-resignation-over-plebgate-claims |title=Andrew Mitchell announces resignation over 'plebgate' claims|work=Channel 4 News |date=19 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/chief-whip-andrew-mitchell-resigns-over-plebgate-8218881.html|title=Chief Whip Andrew Mitchell resigns over 'Plebgate'|work=The Independent|date=19 October 2012}}</ref> Members of the [[West Midlands Police|West Midlands]] branch of the [[Police Federation of England and Wales]], [[Shadow Home Secretary]] [[Yvette Cooper]] and a [[Editorial|leader column]] in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' called on Mitchell to resign or be sacked.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/9602119/Andrew-Mitchell-must-step-down.html |title=Telegraph View \u2013 Andrew Mitchell must step down |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nThe affair has occasionally been referred to as '''\"Plodgate\"''' (\"[[wikt:plod#Etymology 3|plod]]\" being mildly derogatory [[British slang]] for a police officer).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2012/12/will-the-plod-gate-revelations-change-how-voters-think-about-class-attacks/|title=Will 'plod-gate' make voters more sceptical of class-based political attacks?|work=The Spectator |date=23 December 2012|accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Week]]'' magazine called it \"'''Gategate'''\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/politics/gategate/49169/gategate-friends-ids-take-pleasure-andrew-mitchell-gaffe  |title=Gategate: Andrew Mitchell fails to deny calling police \u2018plebs\u2019  |work=The Week |date=24 September 2012}}</ref> which was picked up by ''[[Business Insider]]'', saying that this use of the [[-gate|-gate suffix for scandals]] had taken \"the practice to its logical conclusion\" as a \"new height of absurdity\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Adam |title=The Latest Political Scandal In London Has The Best Name Yet |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/gategate-the-latest-absurd-uk-scandal-2012-9?r=US&IR=T |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\n==Apologies and eventual resignation==\nMitchell apologised on 21 September, saying \"I admit I did not treat the police with the respect they deserve\", but he denied swearing or calling the officers \"plebs\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19671093 |title=Chief Whip Andrew Mitchell apologises to police |publisher=BBC News |date=21 September 2012}}</ref> However, he later admitted saying: \"I thought you guys were supposed to fucking help us.\"<ref name=telown /> John Tully, chairman of the [[Metropolitan Police Federation]], said that Mitchell's account was contradicted by notes made by two officers at the scene.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.sky.com/story/988170/mitchell-faces-calls-to-quit-over-police-row |title=Mitchell Row: PC's Widower Urges PM To Act |date=22 September 2012\n|publisher=Sky News}}</ref> The Chairman of the [[Police Federation of England and Wales]] commented that \"It is hard to fathom how someone who holds the police in such contempt could be allowed to hold a public office. Mr Mitchell's half-hearted apology for the comments made whilst leaving Downing Street will do little to build bridges with the police\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.polfed.org/newsroom/554.aspx |title=Federation response to comments made by Chief Whip, Andrew Mitchell |publisher=Police Federation of England and Wales |date=21 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nFive days after the event, on 24 September, Mitchell apologised a second time for his behaviour, saying \"I didn't show the police the amount of respect which I should have done\", but stated that he did not use the words that had been attributed to him. He did not specify which words he was referring to. John Tully said \"It is not the words, police officers are quite thick skinned, what infuriates me here is that a minister [Andrew Mitchell] is saying police officers are liars. There is a clear difference of opinion, and we need to establish what happened.\"<ref name=telref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9562468/Andrew-Mitchell-Police-refuse-second-apology-as-calls-for-inquiry-grow.html |title=Andrew Mitchell: Police refuse second apology as calls for inquiry grow |work=The Telegraph |date=24 September 2012}}</ref> The same day, [[Secretary of the Cabinet (United Kingdom)|Cabinet Secretary]] [[Jeremy Heywood|Sir Jeremy Heywood]] confirmed in a letter to Shadow Home Secretary Yvette Cooper that there would be no inquiry into Andrew Mitchell's outburst because, although the outburst was disappointing, the officer had accepted Mitchell's apology.<ref name=BBC19707950>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19707950 |title=Andrew Mitchell avoids investigation over police row |publisher=BBC News |date=24 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nMitchell's apologies failed to end the criticism, and media commentators and political opponents continued to call for his resignation.<ref name=BBC19922026>{{cite news |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19922026 |title=Andrew Mitchell resigns over police comments row |date=19 October 2012}}</ref> Finally, Mitchell resigned on 19 October, stating, \"It has become clear to me that whatever the rights and wrongs of the matter I will not be able to fulfill my duties as we both would wish. [...] Nor is it fair to continue to put my family and colleagues through this upsetting and damaging publicity\". He continued to maintain that he had not used the word \"pleb\". The Police Federation of England and Wales issued a statement that it regarded his resignation as the end of the matter, and would seek no further action.<ref name=BBC19922026 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19922026|title=Andrew Mitchell resigns over police comments row |publisher=BBC News |date=20 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Doubts over police version of events==\nIn mid-December 2012, CCTV footage of the incident was released, which Mitchell insisted backed up his version of events. The footage shows a brief interaction between Mitchell and the police and there was no crowd of tourists outside the gates.<ref name=cctv />\n\nOn 18 December 2012, journalist [[Michael Crick]] and former [[The Cook Report]] producer Philip Braund identified the author of the 20 September email as a police officer and challenged his account. The officer admitted that he was not present and that the email was false.<ref name=c4>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |publisher=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012 |timecaption=\"Plebgate row\", event occurs at |time=16:00}}</ref> Police logs and the supporting email had both claimed that \"several members of the public\" were present, that they had heard the exchange and were \"visibly shocked\". The email alleged that \"Other people/tourists standing with us were also shocked and some were even, inadvertently, filming the incident\". However, the CCTV footage shows only a single member of the public stopping to look on from an otherwise empty section of street immediately outside the gates.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |publisher=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012 |timecaption=\"Plebgate row\", event occurs at |time=07:20}}</ref>\n\nIt further transpired that Police Federation officers from around the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] who met with Mitchell had claimed he refused to give his side of events, a claim thrown into question by a recording of that meeting.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/andrew-mitchell-plebgate-police-cctv-downing-street |title=CCTV casts doubt on account of Andrew Mitchell exchange |publisher=Channel 4 News |date=18 December 2012 |timecaption=\"Plebgate row\", event occurs at |time=09:16}}</ref> Mitchell{{mdash}}the MP for [[Sutton Coldfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton Coldfield]] in the West Midlands{{mdash}}had met with three representatives from the [[West Midlands Police|West Midlands]], [[Warwickshire Police|Warwickshire]] and [[West Mercia Police|West Mercia]] forces at his constituency office on 12 October to discuss the incident, after which the officers gave interviews about what had been discussed at the meeting. They claimed Mitchell had not given a full account of the disagreement, but a transcript of the recording he made indicated he had spoken at length about the incident.<ref name=Guardian-2013-10-16/>\n\n==Operation Alice==\nFollowing these revelations, calls were made for the events to be fully investigated. The Metropolitan Police revealed that the investigation, which had started shortly after the leak of the police log,<ref name=BBC19707950 /> now had a team of thirty officers investigating the allegations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pleb row: Calls for inquiry into Andrew Mitchell case |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/plebgate-met-promises-fast-response-to-andrew-mitchell-row |work=Channel 4 News |date=19 December 2012}}</ref> The operation, \"Operation Alice\", was led by the head of the Metropolitan Police's [[Directorate of Professional Standards]], Deputy Assistant Commissioner [[Pat Gallan]].<ref name=bbc20795489>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20795489 |title='Plebgate': Second man arrested in Metropolitan Police inquiry |publisher=BBC News |date=20 December 2012}}</ref> On 23 December, the [[Metropolitan Police Commissioner]] [[Bernard Hogan-Howe]] returned from his holiday to promise \"a ruthless search for the truth\" of the affair.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-20829901|title='Plebgate': Met Police vows 'ruthless' search for truth|publisher=BBC News|date=23 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported on 24 March 2013 that ten police officers and one civilian were suspected of involvement.<ref name=tel10>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/9951254/Ten-police-officers-investigated-over-Plebgate-row-that-cost-Andrew-Mitchell-his-job.html |title=Ten police officers investigated over 'Plebgate' row that cost Andrew Mitchell his job |date=24 March 2013 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Seven of those officers and the one civilian fell under Operation Alice, with the investigation into the three Police Federation officers, Ken Mackaill, Chris Jones & Stuart Hinton,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.policeoracle.com/news/Police+Performance/2013/Mar/26/More-Fed-Officials-Face-Plebgate-Probe_62605.html |title=More Fed Officials Face 'Plebgate' Probe |work=Police Oracle |date=26 March 2013}}</ref> being a separate investigation by the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]].<ref name=tel10 />\n\nThe police submitted their report to the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] on 28 March. It contained evidence of alleged leaks, but not that officers had lied about what Mitchell said. The CPS indicated that it was unhappy with the file, referring to it as \"initial papers\" and saying that they were awaiting the conclusion of the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/mar/28/lebgate-file-contains-no-evidence-that-police-lied |title='Plebgate' file passed to prosecutors contains no evidence that police lied |date=29 March 2013 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> At the same time, Mitchell started libel proceedings against ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', the paper that broke the story.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21969990 |title=Andrew Mitchell to sue Sun newspaper over 'plebgate' |date=29 March 2013 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 31 March, as a result of the apparent leaking of the report, he lodged a complaint with the IPCC, accusing the police of a continued campaign to destroy his career.  [[Keith Vaz]], chairman of the [[Home Affairs Select Committee|Commons Home Affairs committee]], said that this illustrated why his committee had always called for the investigation to be run by the IPCC rather than by the police themselves.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/andrew-mitchell-complains-to-police-watchdog-over-scotland-yard-handling-of-plebgate-row-report-8555427.html |title=Andrew Mitchell complains to police watchdog over Scotland Yard handling of 'Plebgate' row report  |date=31 March 2013 |work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2013, Operation Alice had cost an estimated \u00a3144,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-22117380 |title='Plebgate': Police inquiry costs reach \u00a3144,000 |date=11 April 2013 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2014, it was reported that the investigation's conclusion revealed the police had obtained the mobile phone records of the Political Editor of ''The Sun'' without his knowledge, through use of the [[Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000]], and in breach of the usual safeguards for the protection of journalistic sources. They were thereby able to unmask the identity of the whistle-blower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/leveson-inquiry/11077481/A-perfect-example-of-the-need-for-a-free-press.html|title=A perfect example of the need for a free press|first=Telegraph|last=View|date=5 September 2014|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Investigations and arrests===\nIn March 2013, three officers from the [[Diplomatic Protection Unit]] were arrested: one on suspicion of [[misconduct in a public office]], one on suspicion of unauthorised disclosure of information to the media and one on suspicion of both offences.<ref name=bbcheld>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21299860 |title='Plebgate': Police officer held over inquiry |publisher=BBC News |date=1 February 2013}}</ref> Another man, a relative of one of the arrested officers,<ref name=guarpf>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/mar/24/plebgate-police-federation-andrew-mitchell |title=Plebgate affair: Police Federation staff quizzed over Andrew Mitchell remarks |date=24 March 2013 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> was arrested on suspicion of \"intentionally encouraging or assisting the commission of an indictable offence\", relating to misconduct in a public office.<ref name=bbcheld /> In addition, another four members of the Diplomatic Protection Group became the subject of disciplinary investigations.<ref name=guarpf /> Under a separate but related inquiry by the IPCC, three members of the Police Federation were investigated for alleged misconduct over comments they made to the media.<ref name=tel10 />\n\nIn June 2013 two more arrests were made, with one of those arrested being a serving police officer. The officer, one of the four Diplomatic Protection officers already undergoing disciplinary investigation, was arrested on suspicion of misconduct in a public office and the civilian on suspicion of assisting an offender.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22919576 |title=Two arrested in 'plebgate' probe |publisher=BBC News |date=15 June 2013}}</ref> In September 2013 it was revealed eight people had been bailed over the issue, including five police officers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24230733 |title=Police Officers Bailed |publisher=BBC |date=24 September 2013}}</ref> The lengthy investigation was criticised by the former [[Director of Public Prosecutions]], [[Lord MacDonald]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24140199 |title='Plebgate' inquiry delay criticised by ex-DPP |publisher=BBC |date=18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Criminal conviction of PC Keith Wallis ===\nOn 10 January 2014, Police Constable Keith Wallis pleaded guilty at the Central Criminal Court, the [[Old Bailey]], to a charge of [[misconduct in a public office]] relating to the email he had sent to [[John Randall MP]]. This prompted the Metropolitan Police Commissioner, Sir [[Bernard Hogan-Howe]], to issue a public apology to Andrew Mitchell:\n\n::\"The evidence against PC Wallis was such that he pleaded guilty. To lie about witnessing something and provide a false account falls way below the standards that I and his colleagues expect of officers. His actions have also negatively impacted upon public trust and confidence in the integrity of police officers. I would also like to apologise to Mr Mitchell that a Met officer clearly lied about seeing him behaving in a certain manner. I will be writing to him offering to meet and apologise in person. I expect my officers to serve the public without fear or favour. Where officers break the law they must expect to be held to account and answer for what they have done.\"<ref>{{cite news| last1=Davenport| first1=Justin| last2=Cecil| first2=Nicholas| date= 10 January 2014| title=Plebgate scandal: Met police apology to Andrew Mitchell after officer admits lie| url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/plebgate-scandal-met-police-apology-to-andrew-mitchell-after-officer-admits-lie-9051453.html| newspaper=London Evening Standard|location=London| publisher=Evening Standard Limited}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2014, Wallis was sentenced to twelve months imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-26064536 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate' PC Keith Wallis jailed for a year |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Seven findings of police misconduct===\nSeven police officers were found to have committed misconduct in relation to Plebgate, one criminally, three at the level of [[gross misconduct]] and three more as misconduct but not gross misconduct requiring dismissal from the service. Specifically:\n\n* on 26 February 2014 Keith Wallis was dismissed for his criminal conduct in this matter and undisclosed business interests;\n* on 26 February 2014 James Glanville was also dismissed for gross misconduct in data handling <ref name=BBC-26Feb2014>{{cite news|title=Met pair dismissed over 'Plebgate'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26358662|accessdate=26 February 2014|publisher=BBC News|date=26 February 2014}}</ref>\n* on 30 April 2014 PC Gillian Weatherley was also dismissed for gross misconduct for leaks to the press.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24548645 |title='Plebgate' row: Timeline |publisher=BBC |date=30 April 2014|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref>\n* on 21 May 2014 Susan Johnson was dismissed for gross misconduct \"in relation to honesty and integrity; confidentiality; discreditable conduct and challenging and reporting improper conduct\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/plebgate-officers-keith-wallis-james-glanville-dismissed-metropolitan-police-1438052 |title='Plebgate' row: Timeline |publisher=BBC |date=21 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n* on 23 May an allegation against PC James Addison was found \"not proven\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27540822 |title='Plebgate' affair: No misconduct by officer |publisher=BBC |date=23 May 2014}}</ref>\n* Three further officers were found guilty of lower level misconduct.\n\n===Federation officers===\nThe IPCC investigation of the three Federation officers, Chris Jones, Stuart Hinton and Ken MacKaill, was on hold for much of 2014, pending a judicial review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-25705250 |title='Plebgate' affair: Police Federation launches legal action |publisher=BBC |date=12 January 2014}}</ref> However, on 3 November 2014, this application was unsuccessful, with the three forces' investigations branded by the administrative court \"a car crash\" and so legally flawed that they were \"invalid and of no effect\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/plebgate-probe-decision-legally-flawed-7893374|title=Plebgate probe decision 'legally flawed'|first=James|last=Cartledge|date=7 October 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nTwo of these officers were also accused of lying to Parliament in their evidence to the Home Affairs Select Committee in the account they gave of their disciplinary record (stating they had no record when in fact they did), and were recalled by the committee to justify this.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Townsend |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/nov/03/plebgate-police-federation-select-committee |title=Plebgate police told: apologise or face a charge of contempt &#124; The Observer |work=The Guardian }}</ref> They subsequently apologised.\n\n==IPCC conclusions==\n\nWest Mercia Police launched an investigation into the conduct of the three police officers who spoke with Mitchell at his constituency office, but concluded they should not be disciplined.<ref name=Birmingham-Mail-2013-10-18>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/midland-chief-constables-quizzed-plebgate-6203811 |title=Midland chief constables to be quizzed about 'Plebgate' row at select committee |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> On 15 October 2013, the IPCC criticised three Police Federation Officers for their version of events. The Home Secretary, [[Theresa May]], was also critical, saying the police were wrong to say they had no case to answer and calling for the officers to be disciplined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10381529/Discipline-Plebgate-police-and-say-sorry-to-Andrew-Mitchell-Theresa-May-tells-forces.html |title=Discipline Plebgate police and say sorry to Andrew Mitchell, Theresa May tells forces |author=Martin Evans |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 October 2013 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24536328 |title='Plebgate' police officers' honesty queried |publisher=BBC |date=15 October 2013 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> At [[Prime Minister's Questions]] on 16 October 2013, David Cameron said that Mitchell was \"owed an apology\" over the Plebgate affair.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-24546370 |publisher=BBC News |title=Plebgate: PM says police owe Andrew Mitchell apology  |date=16 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe findings of the IPCC report were criticised by the three police forces concerned, as well as by the [[Police and Crime Commissioner]] for Warwickshire, [[Ron Ball]]. This prompted the IPCC's Deputy Chair, [[Deborah Glass]], to respond with clarification of its conclusions. In a letter to Ball, Glass said that West Mercia had changed its mind over whether to discipline the officers before the final publication of its report.<ref name=Guardian-2013-10-16>{{cite news|first=Nicholas |last=Watt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/16/plebgate-watchdog-police-watered-conclusions-investigation |title=Plebgate: watchdog says police watered down conclusions of investigation |newspaper=The Guardian |date=16 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> Her comments led to media speculation that senior police officers could have interfered with the investigation.<ref name=BBC-2013-10-18>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-24583765 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate' row prompts West Mercia review  |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> Ball subsequently requested a review of West Mercia's inquiry. \"That is a very serious allegation and I want to understand the exact circumstances of the investigative approval process.\"<ref name=BBC-2013-10-18/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/437608/Police-best-in-the-world-insists-PM |title=Police best in the world insists PM |newspaper=Daily Express |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> West Mercia then launched an investigation into issues raised by the IPCC.<ref name=BBC-2013-10-18/>\n\nOn 21 October 2013, the three officers concerned{{mdash}}Ken MacKaill, Stuart Hinton, and Chris Jones{{mdash}}issued a statement in which they apologised for their \"poor judgement\" in briefing the media about their meeting, and said that they did not intend to mislead the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24615491 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate' meeting police apologise for briefing  |date=21 October 2013 |accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref> Along with their respective Chief Constables, the three officers appeared before the [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] on 23 October in which they told MPs their account of the meeting with Mitchell had been \"accurate\" and they stood by it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24629610 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate': Police officers stand by account of Mitchell meeting  |date=23 October 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref> The Committee subsequently called them back, believing that they had misled it. In November 2013 the IPCC announced it would conduct its own investigation into the behaviour of the officers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24787557 |publisher=BBC News |title='Plebgate': Officers face fresh inquiry over Mitchell meeting  |date=3 November 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref> In the wake of the announcement, Ron Ball expressed his concerns about the legality of a new investigation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/news/10781512.New_Plebgate_probe__may_not_be_legally_sound____police_commissioner/ |title=New Plebgate probe 'may not be legally sound' \u2013 police commissioner |newspaper=Worcester News |publisher=Newsquest |date=3 November 2013 |accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHome Secretary Theresa May referred to this event, along with others, in a speech on 21 May 2014 which demanded the police address issues of honesty and integrity and that the Federation reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27504422 |title=Theresa May urges Police Federation reform |publisher=BBC |date=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Libel trial==\nOn 17 November 2014 a [[Civil law (legal system)|civil]] [[English defamation law|libel case]] for the allegations began oral hearings at the [[Royal Courts of Justice]], before [[John Mitting|Mr Justice Mitting]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/plebgate-trial-sifts-fiction-from-fact-pc-plod-is-the-toyland-constable-is-he-not-9866524.html|title=Plebgate trial sifts fiction from fact|publisher=}}</ref> In these proceedings two cases were joined: the alleged libel of Mitchell by ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', and, alternatively, the alleged libel of PC Rowland by Mitchell.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Darwar|first1=Anil|title=Plebgate MP in \u201816 other clashes\u2019|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/526710/Plebgate-MP-16-other-clashes|accessdate=17 November 2014|publisher=Express Newspapers|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> One of the alleged incidents, which had occurred in November 2005, involved Mitchell claiming that he was too important to stop for a police officer, and a direct insult addressed to the officer involved.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mitchell v News Group Newspapers Ltd [2014] EWHC 3590 (QB) (31 October 2014)|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/QB/2014/3590.html|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mitchell decision considers court\u2019s approach to admitting evidence of \"similar facts\"|url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=5c8ef65e-fdb6-4703-899a-bfc565ada751|accessdate=17 November 2014|date=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November Mr Justice Mitting found: \"I am satisfied at least on the balance of probabilities that Mr Mitchell did speak the words alleged or something so close to them as to amount to the same including the politically toxic word pleb.\" In consequence Mitchell lost the libel cases and became liable for both the ''Sun''{{'}}s and PC Rowland's costs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-30235009|title=Andrew Mitchell 'probably called police plebs', judge rules |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=27 November 2014 |website=BBC News | accessdate=27 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Downing Street}}\n\n[[Category:History of the Metropolitan Police]]\n[[Category:Police misconduct in England]]\n[[Category:Police operations in the United Kingdom|A]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2012 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2012 in London]]\n[[Category:2012 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Downing Street]]\n", "name_user": "Sodacan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvestigations and arrests:wl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plebgate"}
{"title_page": "Anita Odia", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian actress and producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Anita Odia\n| image        = Anita Caroline Odia.jpg\n| caption      = Odia in 2019\n| birth_name   = Anita Caroline Odia\n| birth_date   = February 12\n| birth_place  = [[Ikeja, Lagos]], Nigeria\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|[[Model (person)|Model]]|[[actress]]|[[film producer]]}}\n| years_active = 2012-present\n| known_for    = {{unbulleted list\n  |''[[Beauty of The Mind, (2015 film)|Beauty of The Mind]]''\n  |''[[The Silverspoon (2017 film)|The Silverspoon]]''\n  |''[[Dry Tears (2018 Nigerian film)|Dry Tears]]''\n    }}\n| awards       = [[Anita Odia#awards and recognition|See below]]\n| net_worth    = \n| website      = {{URL|akeyssproductions.com/}}\n| signature    = Anita Odia Signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Anita Caroline Odia''' is a Nigerian [[actress]] and [[Film producer|producer]] born on the 12th of February, in Lagos - Nigeria. She is the Chief Executive Officer of A. Keyss Productions,<ref>http://www.findglocal.com/NG/Gwarinpa/1690889887802566/A.-Keyss-Productions</ref> a film production company in the Federal Capital Territory, [[Abuja]] which is into making high budget Movies, Skits and Web series for the Nigerian market, such as: Beauty of The Mind, The Silverspoon and Dry Tears.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnita Caroline Odia was Born on February 12 in Ikeja, Lagos - Nigeria and she is the first of five children by a Cameroonian mother and a Nigerian father. Although born in Lagos, Anita's earliest years, including her primary education were spent in Bamenda, a city in northwestern Cameroon, before she returned to Nigeria for her Secondary School Education in Lagos and Kano states. She earned a bachelor's degree in Education (B.Ed) at the University of Calabar, situated in the Capital of Cross River state, a port city in southern Nigeria that shares a border with Cameroon.\n\n==Career==\n\nAnita picked up interest in acting while at the University which led her to take part in a film training workshop in Nigeria's the federal capital, [[Abuja]], in 2010, organized by the [[New York Film Academy]] in a calculated move that launched her into her acting career with a Diploma in [[acting]]. Having, prior to that registered as a member of the [[Actors Guild of Nigeria]], [[Abuja]] Chapter, she soon landed her first role in the movie, Real Wife in 2012 and by her second role in 2013 in the movie Ladies Affair, Anita's love and passion for acting and the movie industry was no longer in doubt. Subsequently (By 2014) through her \u2018A Keyss Productions\u2019, she produced her first movie; \u2018Beauty of The Mind\u2019 where she played the role of a Supporting Actress which earned 2 nominations at the International Film Festival in London (which year) as well as a nomination in 2018, for the Best Independent Film Supporting Actress in the Hollywood And African Prestigious Awards \u2013 HAPAwards, a United States of America awards which recognizes outstanding individuals whose lives have been marked by extraordinary personal and professional accomplishments.\n\nWith such astounding success of her first film, Anita's wade into the movie production industry, alongside acting became swifter and more sure footed as she featured in several other movies such as: From the Street, Stay with Me, Ekwueme and His Investment (in which she acted alongside the Popular Nkem Owoh and the multiple awards winning Daniel K. Daniel), Eno my Calabar Love (starring alongside Ini Edo), and Ojuko The War Lord (featured alongside Eniola Badmus and Queen Nwokoye). By 2015, under her production company, A Keyss Productions, she Co-Produced Fast Cash and then Silver Spoon and Dry Tears both of which were produced solely in 2017 and 2019 respectively.\n\n==Personal life==\nAnita Caroline Odia grew up in [[Bamenda]] (northwest), [[Cameroon]] where she had her my primary school education and later relocated back to Nigeria to complete her Secondary School education.\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" background: #f9f9f0;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Director\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|2012\n| ''Real Wives''<ref>https://www.nollywoodreinvented.com/2012/10/real-wives.html</ref>\n| Actress\n| Tchidi Chikere\n| With [[Stephanie Okereke]]\n|-\n|2013\n|''Ladies Affair''<ref>https://www.pinterest.com/pin/396668679652961557/</ref><ref>https://ng.linkedin.com/in/amaechi-ukeje-b4475b53</ref>\n| Actress\n| Amechi Ukeje\n|with [[Chika Ike]], [[Funke Akindele]], [[Ebube Nwagbo]] & [[Juliet Ibrahim]]\n|-\n|2014\n|''Beauty of The Mind''<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5074428/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl</ref><ref>https://nlist.ng/title/beauty-of-the-mind-643/credits/</ref>\n| Actress, Producer\n| Okey Zebulu <ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/Beauty-Chinyere-Wilfred-Bryan-Okwara/dp/B07KMNG57L</ref>\n|with [[Nse Ikpe Etim]], [[Bryan Okwara]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017\n|''Osinachi My Wife''<ref>https://nlist.ng/title/osinachi-my-wife-11772/reviews/</ref>\n|Actress\n|Chijioke Okeke\n|with Yule Edochie, Harry B\n|-\n|The Silverspoon <ref>http://onobello.com/the-silver-spoon-desmond-elliot-wole-ojo-yvonne-jedege-more-for-new-movie-watch-trailer/</ref><ref>http://thenet.ng/silver-spoon-wole-ojo-yvonne-jegede-cast-talk-new-desmond-elliot-movie/</ref>\n|Actress, Producer \n|[[Desmond Elliot]]\n|with [[Wole Ojo]], Sophie Alakija, [[Yvonne Jegede]], [[Ayo Adesanya]], Chucks Chyke\n|-\n|''Fast Cash''<ref>http://blog.irokotv.com/2016/07/07/watch-fast-cash-irokotv/</ref>\n|Actress, Co-Producer\n|Okey Zubelu\n|with [[Funnybone]], Oma Nnadi, [[Kiki Omeili]], [[Tamara Eteimo]], [[Mary Lazarus]] & Klint D Drunk\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|''From The Stress''\n|Actress\n|Tola Balogun\n|with Okey Uzoeshi, [[Ivie Okujaye]]\n|-\n|Dry Tears <ref>https://web.facebook.com/350662741803855/photos/a.355373301332799/1157246267812161/?type=1&theater</ref>\n|Actress, Producer \n|Sadiq Sule\n|with Ninolowo Bolanle, [[Bimbo Ademoye]], Ijeoma Peters\n|-\n|}\n\n==awards and recognition==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Event\n!Prize\n!Recipient \n!Result\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Zulu African Film Academy Awards]]\n|Best Actress & Best Scriptwriter\n|Beauty of The Mind\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|[[BFI London Film Festival]] - UK <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BFI_London_Film_Festival</ref>\n|Best Independent Film \n|Beauty of The Mind \n|{{nominated}}<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BFI_London_Film_Festival</ref><ref>https://theworldsatellite.com/2020/01/20/anita-keyss-a-testament-of-the-nollywood-dream/</ref>\n|-\n|Hollywood and African Prestigious Awards, Los Angeles\n|Best Independent Film Supporting Actress \n|Beauty of The Mind <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5074428/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl</ref>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odia, Anita}}\n[[Category:Living people|Odia, Anita]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian actress and producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Anita Odia\n| image        = Anita Caroline Odia.jpg\n| caption      = Odia in 2019\n| birth_name   = Anita Caroline Odia\n| birth_date   = February 12\n| birth_place  = [[Ikeja, Lagos]], Nigeria\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|[[Model (person)|Model]]|[[actress]]|[[film producer]]}}\n| years_active = 2012-present\n| known_for    = {{unbulleted list\n  |''[[Beauty of The Mind, (2015 film)|Beauty of The Mind]]''\n  |''[[The Silverspoon (2017 film)|The Silverspoon]]''\n  |''[[Dry Tears (2018 Nigerian film)|Dry Tears]]''\n    }}\n| awards       = [[Anita Odia#awards and recognition|See below]]\n| net_worth    = \n| website      = {{URL|akeyssproductions.com/}}\n| signature    = Anita Odia Signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Anita Caroline Odia''' is a Nigerian [[actress]] and [[Film producer|producer]] born on the 12th of February, in Lagos - Nigeria. She is the Chief Executive Officer of A. Keyss Productions,<ref>http://www.findglocal.com/NG/Gwarinpa/1690889887802566/A.-Keyss-Productions</ref> a film production company in the Federal Capital Territory, [[Abuja]] which is into making high budget Movies, Skits and Web series for the Nigerian market, such as: Beauty of The Mind, The Silverspoon and Dry Tears.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnita Caroline Odia was Born on February 12 in Ikeja, Lagos - Nigeria and she is the first of five children by a Cameroonian mother and a Nigerian father. Although born in Lagos, Anita's earliest years, including her primary education were spent in Bamenda, a city in northwestern Cameroon, before she returned to Nigeria for her Secondary School Education in Lagos and Kano states. She earned a bachelor's degree in Education (B.Ed) at the University of Calabar, situated in the Capital of Cross River state, a port city in southern Nigeria that shares a border with Cameroon.\n\n==Career==\n\nAnita picked up interest in acting while at the University which led her to take part in a film training workshop in Nigeria's the federal capital, [[Abuja]], in 2010, organized by the [[New York Film Academy]] in a calculated move that launched her into her acting career with a Diploma in [[acting]]. Having, prior to that registered as a member of the [[Actors Guild of Nigeria]], [[Abuja]] Chapter, she soon landed her first role in the movie, Real Wife in 2012 and by her second role in 2013 in the movie Ladies Affair, Anita's love and passion for acting and the movie industry was no longer in doubt. Subsequently (By 2014) through her \u2018A Keyss Productions\u2019, she produced her first movie; \u2018Beauty of The Mind\u2019 where she played the role of a Supporting Actress which earned 2 nominations at the International Film Festival in London (which year) as well as a nomination in 2018, for the Best Independent Film Supporting Actress in the Hollywood And African Prestigious Awards \u2013 HAPAwards, a United States of America awards which recognizes outstanding individuals whose lives have been marked by extraordinary personal and professional accomplishments.\n\nWith such astounding success of her first film, Anita's wade into the movie production industry, alongside acting became swifter and more sure footed as she featured in several other movies such as: From the Street, Stay with Me, Ekwueme and His Investment (in which she acted alongside the Popular Nkem Owoh and the multiple awards winning Daniel K. Daniel), Eno my Calabar Love (starring alongside Ini Edo), and Ojuko The War Lord (featured alongside Eniola Badmus and Queen Nwokoye). By 2015, under her production company, A Keyss Productions, she Co-Produced Fast Cash and then Silver Spoon and Dry Tears both of which were produced solely in 2017 and 2019 respectively.\n\n==Personal life==\nAnita Caroline Odia grew up in [[Bamenda]] (northwest), [[Cameroon]] where she had her my primary school education and later relocated back to Nigeria to complete her Secondary School education.\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" background: #f9f9f0;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Director\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|2012\n| ''Real Wives''<ref>https://www.nollywoodreinvented.com/2012/10/real-wives.html</ref>\n| Actress\n| Tchidi Chikere\n| With [[Stephanie Okereke]]\n|-\n|2013\n|''Ladies Affair''<ref>https://www.pinterest.com/pin/396668679652961557/</ref><ref>https://ng.linkedin.com/in/amaechi-ukeje-b4475b53</ref>\n| Actress\n| Amechi Ukeje\n|with [[Chika Ike]], [[Funke Akindele]], [[Ebube Nwagbo]] & [[Juliet Ibrahim]]\n|-\n|2014\n|''Beauty of The Mind''<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5074428/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl</ref><ref>https://nlist.ng/title/beauty-of-the-mind-643/credits/</ref>\n| Actress, Producer\n| Okey Zebulu <ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/Beauty-Chinyere-Wilfred-Bryan-Okwara/dp/B07KMNG57L</ref>\n|with [[Nse Ikpe Etim]], [[Bryan Okwara]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017\n|''Osinachi My Wife''<ref>https://nlist.ng/title/osinachi-my-wife-11772/reviews/</ref>\n|Actress\n|Chijioke Okeke\n|with Yule Edochie, Harry B\n|-\n|The Silverspoon <ref>http://onobello.com/the-silver-spoon-desmond-elliot-wole-ojo-yvonne-jedege-more-for-new-movie-watch-trailer/</ref><ref>http://thenet.ng/silver-spoon-wole-ojo-yvonne-jegede-cast-talk-new-desmond-elliot-movie/</ref>\n|Actress, Producer \n|[[Desmond Elliot]]\n|with [[Wole Ojo]], Sophie Alakija, [[Yvonne Jegede]], [[Ayo Adesanya]], Chucks Chyke\n|-\n|''Fast Cash''<ref>http://blog.irokotv.com/2016/07/07/watch-fast-cash-irokotv/</ref>\n|Actress, Co-Producer\n|Okey Zubelu\n|with [[Funnybone]], Oma Nnadi, [[Kiki Omeili]], [[Tamara Eteimo]], [[Mary Lazarus]] & Klint D Drunk\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|''From The Stress''\n|Actress\n|Tola Balogun\n|with Okey Uzoeshi, [[Ivie Okujaye]]\n|-\n|Dry Tears <ref>https://web.facebook.com/350662741803855/photos/a.355373301332799/1157246267812161/?type=1&theater</ref>\n|Actress, Producer \n|Sadiq Sule\n|with Ninolowo Bolanle, [[Bimbo Ademoye]], Ijeoma Peters\n|-\n|}\n\n==awards and recognition==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Event\n!Prize\n!Recipient \n!Result\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Zulu African Film Academy Awards]]\n|Best Actress & Best Scriptwriter\n|Beauty of The Mind\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=|2018\n|[[BFI London Film Festival]] - UK <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BFI_London_Film_Festival</ref>\n|Best Independent Film \n|Beauty of The Mind \n|{{nominated}}<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BFI_London_Film_Festival</ref><ref>https://theworldsatellite.com/2020/01/20/anita-keyss-a-testament-of-the-nollywood-dream/</ref>\n|-\n|Hollywood and African Prestigious Awards, Los Angeles\n|Best Independent Film Supporting Actress \n|Beauty of The Mind <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5074428/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl</ref>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odia, Anita}}\n[[Category:Living people|Odia, Anita]]\n", "name_user": "Nnadi Duke", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eawards and recognition", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anita_Odia"}
{"title_page": "Krush (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name = Krush\n| type = studio\n| artist = [[DJ Krush]]\n| cover = DJ Krush - Krush.jpg\n| alt = \n| released = {{Start date|1994|01|21}} ([[Japan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/goods/detail/151001|title=DJ Krush - Krush|work=[[Billboard Japan]]|accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref><br/>{{Start date|1995}} (worldwide)<ref name=allmusic/>\n| recorded = \n| studio = \n| genre = [[hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[trip hop]]\n| length = {{Duration|m=52|s=20}}\n| label = [[Nippon Columbia]], [[Shadow Records]]\n| producer = [[DJ Krush]]\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year = \n| next_title = [[Strictly Turntablized]]\n| next_year = 1994\n}}\n'''''Krush''''' is the debut solo studio album by Japanese hip hop producer [[DJ Krush]]. It was released in 1994.\n\nThe 1995 re-release edition does not include \"B-Boy Mastamind\".\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/krush-mw0000644926|title=Krush - DJ Krush|work=[[AllMusic]]|first=Ned|last=Raggett|accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\nNed Raggett of [[AllMusic]] gave the album 4 stars out of 5, saying: \"Working with a variety of his countrymen throughout, who tackle everything from guest vocals to a variety of instruments, Krush sets the late-night, smoky urban mood from the start and doesn't let up throughout.\"<ref name=allmusic/> He added: \"Funky beats are spare but effective, launching grooves that unfold just enough over the course of his tracks, edgy and slightly unnerving.\"<ref name=allmusic/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = AM 300 Tag\n| length1 = 0:52\n| title2 = B-Boy Mastamind\n| length2 = 4:17\n| title3 = Mixed Nuts\n| length3 = 1:11\n| title4 = Roll & Tumble\n| length4 = 5:08\n| title5 = Murder of Soul\n| length5 = 5:37\n| title6 = E.A.R.T.H./SOS\n| length6 = 0:52\n| title7 = On the Dub-ble\n| length7 = 5:43\n| 