{"title_page": "Nzhdeh, Armenia", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name =Nzhdeh\n|native_name =\u0546\u056a\u0564\u0565\u0570\n|settlement_type        = [[Community (Armenia)|community]]\n|pushpin_map            =Armenia\n|mapsize                =150px\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of countries|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Armenia}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Administrative divisions of Armenia|Marz (Province)]]\n|subdivision_name1      =[[Syunik Province|Syunik]]\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            = \n|established_title      =\n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = 28.81\n|area_footnotes           = <ref>{{ARMENIAarea|Syunik}}</ref>\n|population_as_of         = 2011\n|population_total =139\n|population_density_km2   =auto\n|timezone =&nbsp;\n|utc_offset             = +4\n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|39|22|31|N|45|59|46|E|region:AM|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = \n|area_code              = \n|website                = \n|footnotes              ={{GEOnet2|32FA881E69ED3774E0440003BA962ED3}}\n}}\n'''Nzhdeh''' ({{lang-hy|\u0546\u056a\u0564\u0565\u0570}}); formerly known as ''Pusak'' ({{lang-hy|\u0553\u0578\u0582\u057d\u0561\u056f}}) and ''Sofulu'', ''Soflu'' ({{lang-hy|\u054d\u0578\u0586\u056c\u0578\u0582}}), is a village and [[Community (Armenia)|rural community]]  in the [[Syunik Province]] of [[Armenia]]. It is named after Armenian military leader [[Garegin Nzhdeh]].\n\nThe community of Nzhdeh includes the villages of Nzhdeh and [[Tsghuni]]. The [[Statistical Committee of Armenia]] reported the community's population as 188 in 2010,<ref>{{ARMSTATdata|44}}</ref> up from 185 at the 2001 census.<ref name=census>{{ArmenianCensus|210}}</ref> The village's population was 92 at the 2011 census,<ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Results of the 2011 Armenian Census|url=http://armstat.am/file/doc/99483283.pdf|website=Statistical Committee of Armenia}}</ref> down from 114 at the 2001 census.<ref name=census/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Syunik Province]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Syunik}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Syunik Province]]\n[[Category:Communities in Syunik Province]]\n\n{{Syunik-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name =Nzhdeh\n|native_name =\u0546\u056a\u0564\u0565\u0570\n|settlement_type        = [[Community (Armenia)|community]]\n|pushpin_map            =Armenia\n|mapsize                =150px\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of countries|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Armenia}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Administrative divisions of Armenia|Marz (Province)]]\n|subdivision_name1      =[[Syunik Province|Syunik]]\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            = \n|established_title      =\n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = 28.81\n|area_footnotes           = <ref>{{ARMENIAarea|Syunik}}</ref>\n|population_as_of         = 2011\n|population_total =139\n|population_density_km2   =auto\n|timezone =&nbsp;\n|utc_offset             = +4\n|timezone_DST           = \n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|39|22|31|N|45|59|46|E|region:AM|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = \n|area_code              = \n|website                = \n|footnotes              ={{GEOnet2|32FA881E69ED3774E0440003BA962ED3}}\n}}\n'''Nzhdeh''' ({{lang-hy|\u0546\u056a\u0564\u0565\u0570}}); formerly known as ''Pusak'' ({{lang-hy|\u0553\u0578\u0582\u057d\u0561\u056f}}) and ''Sofulu'', ''Soflu'' ({{lang-hy|\u054d\u0578\u0586\u056c\u0578\u0582}}), is a village and [[Community (Armenia)|rural community]]  in the [[Syunik Province]] of [[Armenia]]. It is named after the Armenian military leader [[Garegin Nzhdeh]].\n\nThe community of Nzhdeh includes the villages of Nzhdeh and [[Tsghuni]]. The [[Statistical Committee of Armenia]] reported the community's population as 188 in 2010,<ref>{{ARMSTATdata|44}}</ref> up from 185 at the 2001 census.<ref name=census>{{ArmenianCensus|210}}</ref> The village's population was 92 at the 2011 census,<ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Results of the 2011 Armenian Census|url=http://armstat.am/file/doc/99483283.pdf|website=Statistical Committee of Armenia}}</ref> down from 114 at the 2001 census.<ref name=census/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Syunik Province]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Syunik}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Syunik Province]]\n[[Category:Communities in Syunik Province]]\n\n{{Syunik-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DifferentialSpace", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nzhdeh,_Armenia"}
{"title_page": "Names of God in Islam", "text_new": "{{redirect|al-Badi|the palace in Marrakesh|El Badi Palace}}\n{{short description|Names of God in the Quran and hadith}}\n{{Allah |related}}\n\nIn [[Islam]] God is believed to have 99 Names, known as the '''99 Names of Allah'''  {{transl|ar|\u02beasm\u0101\u02beu ll\u0101hi l-\u1e25usn\u0101}} ({{nowrap|{{lang-ar|\u0623\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646\u0649}}}} '''Beautiful Names of Allah''') They are also called '''99 Attributes of Allah'''. The meaning of the names differs among interpretations.\n\n== Origin ==\n[[File:99names kuwait.jpg|thumb|The 99 names of God on the ceiling of the [[Grand Mosque (Kuwait)|Grand Mosque]] in [[Kuwait]]]]\n\nBy what they said to [[Sahih al-Bukhari|Sahih Bukhari]] Hadith:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sunnah.com/bukhari/80/105|title=Hadith: Book of Invocations - Sahih al-Bukhari - Sunnah.com - Sayings and Teachings of Prophet Muhammad (\u0635\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0648 \u0633\u0644\u0645)|website=sunnah.com|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|[[Abu Hurairah]] reported that Allah has ninety-nine Names, i.e., one hundred minus one, and whoever believes in their meanings and acts accordingly, will enter [[Paradise]]; and Allah is witr (one) and loves 'the witr' (i.e., odd numbers).|sign=|source=Sahih Bukhari, Vol. 8, Book 75, Hadith 419}}\n\nThere is another [[Sahih Muslim]] Hadith:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sunnah.com/bukhari/97/21|title=Hadith - Book of Oneness, Uniqueness of Allah (Tawheed) - Sahih al-Bukhari - Sunnah.com - Sayings and Teachings of Prophet Muhammad (\u0635\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0647 \u0648 \u0633\u0644\u0645)|website=sunnah.com|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Allah's Messenger ([[\ufdfa]]) said, \"Allah has ninety-nine Names, one-hundred less one; and he who memorized them all by heart will enter Paradise.\" To count something means to know it by heart.|sign=|source=Sahih Bukhari, Vol. 9, Book 93, Hadith 489}}\n\nThe [[Quran]] refers to God's ''Most Beautiful Names'' (''al-\u02beasm\u0101\u02be al-\u1e25usn\u00e1'') in several Surahs.<ref>See the [[Surah]] \"[[al-A'raf]]\" ([http://quran.com/7/180 7:180] ), \"[[Al-Isra]]\" ([http://quran.com/17/110 17:110] ), \"[[Ta-Ha]]\" ([http://quran.com/20/8 20:8] ) and \"[[al-Hashr]]\" ([http://quran.com/59/24 59:24] ).</ref> [[Gerhard B\u00f6wering]] refers to Surah 17 [http://quran.com/17/110 (17:110)] as the ''locus classicus'' to which explicit lists of 99 names used to be attached in [[tafsir]]. A cluster of more than a dozen Divine epithets which are included in such lists is found in Surah 59.<ref>http://quran.com/59/22-24 (59:22&ndash;24)</ref> Mystic philosopher [[Ibn Arabi]] surmised that the 99 names are \"outward signs of the universe's inner mysteries\".<ref name=\"morg10\">{{cite book|last=Morgan|first=Diane|authorlink=Diane Morgan|title=Essential Islam: A Comprehensive Guide to Belief and Practice|url=https://archive.org/details/essentialislamco0000morg|url-access=registration|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-36025-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/essentialislamco0000morg/page/10 10]}}</ref>I need your help now, please\n\n==List==\nThere is no universal agreement among Muslims as to what exactly counts as a name of God, and what does not. Additionally, while some names are only in the Quran, and others are only in the hadith, there are some names which appear in both. Different sources give different lists of the 99 names.<ref name=morg10/>\n\nThe following list is based on the one found in the ''[[Jami\u02bf at-Tirmidhi]]'' (9th century). Other hadith, such as those of [[al-Bukhari]], [[Sahih Muslim]], [[Ibn Majah]], [[al-Hakim al-Tirmidhi]] or [[Ibn \u02bfAs\u0101kir]], have variant lists.\n\nAl-Tirmidhi comments on his list:  \"This (version of the) hadith is ''gharib'' [unusual, scarce]; it has been narrated from various routes on the authority of [[Abu Hurairah]], but we do not know of the mention of the Names in the numerous narrations, except this one.\"\nVarious early Muslim exegetes, including [[Ja\u02bffar al-Sadiq]], [[Sufyan ibn `Uyaynah]], [[Ibn Hazm]], [[al-Qurtubi]], [[Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani]], have given their own versions of lists of 99 names.<ref>\nSuhaib Hassan, ''Introduction to the Science of Hadith Classification'' ([http://www.ahya.org/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=7 ahya]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}), cited after [http://wahiduddin.net/words/99_pages/app_c_origins.htm Richard Shelquist (wahiduddin.net)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510223135/http://wahiduddin.net/words/99_pages/app_c_origins.htm |date=2012-05-10 }}{{unreliable source?|date=August 2016}}<!--should cite actual editions, not a random online document--></ref>\n\n{{inline audio|section}}Please note the written Arabic spelling of the names written in Arabic in the table are in the ''vowelled'' Classical/Quranic form (proper = in the Quran and Ah\u0101dith) with the square bracketed \"[.]\" variant of the written Arabic forms given in common or modern texts\u2014usually in media, some long vowels and punctuations are omitted for the easier typing and reading.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! <!--?: F#--> !! Classical [[Arabic alphabet|Arabic]]\n(Quranic/ classical written forms)\n!Modern Standard Arabic (MSA) \n(Variant with vowels/ without vowels)\n![[Transliteration of Arabic|Transliteration]]\n! [[Romanization of Arabic|Romanization]]\n[Various Spellings] \n!Translation{{sup|a}} !! Reference !! grammatical type{{sup|b}}\n|-\n| {{Audio|01-ar-rahman.ogg|1|help=no}} || style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''<big>\\*</big>''' <big>'''\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0651\u062d\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0640\u0670\u0646\u064f'''</big>\n\n<big>'''\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0651\u062d\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0640\u0627\u0646\u064f'''</big>\n\n[<big>'''*'''</big> = ''classical written form'']\n|<big>'''\\* \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0651\u062d\u0645\u0640\u0670\u0646'''</big>\n\n<big>'''\\ \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0651\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0646'''</big>\n\n<big>'''\\* \u0627\u0644\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0640\u0670\u0646'''</big>\n\n<big>'''\u0627\u0644\u0631\u062d\u0645\u0627\u0646'''</big>\n\n[<big>'''*'''</big> = ''classical written form'']\n\n|ar-Ra\u1e25m\u0101n/ ar-Ra\u1e25m\u0101n|| [[Rahman (name)|ar-Ra\u1e25m\u0101n]]\n[Ar-Rahmaan] \n|| The \u0650Beneficient/ All-Compassionate/ Most Gracious/ || Quran: Beginning of every Surah (chapter) except one, and numerous other places. The first verse ('ayat) of [[Surah ar-Rahman]] (Surah 55) consists only of this Name.||style=\"text-align:center;\" | D\n|-\n| {{Audio|02-ar-rahim.ogg|2|help=no}} || style=\"text-align:center;\" | <big>'''\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0651\u062d\u0650\u064a\u0652\u0645\u064f'''</big>\n|'''<big>\\ \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0651\u062d\u064a\u0645</big>'''\n'''<big>\u0627\u0644\u0631\u062d\u064a\u0645</big>'''\n|ar-Ra\u1e25iym/ \nar-Ra\u1e25\u012bm\n| [[Rahim|ar-Ra\u1e25\u012bm]]\n[Ar-Raheem] \n|| The Most Merciful/ Ever-Merciful/ Merciful/ Most Clement || Quran: Beginning of every Surah (chapter) except one, and numerous other places (there are a total of 114 Surahs in the Quran.)||style=\"text-align:center;\" | D\n|-\n| {{Audio|03-al-malik.ogg|3|help=no}} || style=\"text-align:center;\" | <big>'''\\* \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0640\u0670\u0644\u0650\u0643\u064f'''</big>\n\n<big>'''\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0640\u0627\u0644\u0650\u0643\u064f'''</big>\n\n[<big>'''*'''</big> = ''classical written form'']\n|<big>'''\\* \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0640\u0670\u0644\u0643'''</big>\n\n<big>'''\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0644\u0643'''</big>\n\n[<big>'''*'''</big> = ''classical written form'']\n|al-M\u0101lik/ \nal-M\u0101lik\n|| [[Malik|al-M\u0101lik]] \n[al-Maalik]\n|| The King/ Lord/ Sovereign/ Dominion/ Master\n[also means \"the God/ Lord, the One and Only\", \"Possessor of Supreme Power or Authority\"]\n|[http://quran.com/59/23 59:23], [http://quran.com/20/114 20:114], [http://quran.com/23/116 23:116]||style=\"text-align:center;\" | D\n|-\n| {{Audio|04-al-quddus.ogg|4|help=no}} || style=\"text-align:center;\" | <big>'''\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064f\u062f\u064f\u0651\u0648\u0633\u064f'''</big>\n|<big>'''\\ \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0651\u0648\u0633'''</big>\n<big>'''\u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0648\u0633'''</big> \n|al-Qudd\u016bs/\nal-Qudd\u016bs\n||[[Quddus (disambiguation)|al-Quddus]] \n[al-Quddous,\n\nal-Quddoos]\n|| The [[:wikt:\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0633|Holy]]/ All-Holy/ All-Pure/ Sacred/ All-Sacred ||[http://quran.com/59/23 59:23], [http://quran.com/62/1 62:1] ||style=\"text-align:center;\" | D\n|-\n| {{Audio|05-as-salam.ogg|5|help=no}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| <big>'''\\* \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0640\u0670\u0645\u064f'''</big>\n\n<big>'''\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0633\u064e\u0651\u0644\u064e\u0627\u0645\u064f'''</big>\n\n[<big>'''*'''</big> = ''classical written form'']\n\n|'''<big>\\* \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0651\u0644\u0640\u0670\u0645</big>'''\n\n'''<big>\\ \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0651\u0644\u0627\u0645</big>'''\n\n'''\\<big>*</big>''' '''<big>\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0640\u0670\u0645</big>'''\n\n'''<big>\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645</big>'''\n\n[<big>'''*'''</big> = ''classical written form'']\n\n|as-Sal\u0101m/ \nas-Sal\u0101m\n||[[\u0160-L-M|As-Sal\u0101m]] \n[As-Salaam]\n| The Giver of Peace/ [[\u0160-L-M|Peace]]/ All-Calm/ Ever-Tranquil ||[http://quran.com/59/23 59:23]||style=\"text-align:center;\" | D\n|-\n| {{Audio|06-al-mumin.ogg|6|help=no}} || style=\"text-align:center;\" |<big>'''\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u0645\u0650\u0646\u064f'''</big>\n|<big>'''\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0624\u0645\u0646'''</big> \n|al-Mu\u02bfumin/ \nal-Mu\u02bfmin\n||[[Mumin|al-Mu\u02bfmin]]|| The Granter of Security/ the Giver/ Faith/ Supreme Believer (of Belief)/ Giver 